  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Sending Off Guo Jiuzhou on His Inspection Tour
  author: Kim Gu-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Across ten thousand li stretches the heaven-king's land.
    When will the dust of war at last settle?
    The general receives his axe of command,
    while the envoy comes far to bind neighboring states.

    Through mountain and stream to the azure sea he traveled,
    then galloped and galloped toward the purple palace.
    From this day forward let us wipe our eyes clear—
    we shall see the Zhiyuan spring bloom anew.
  footnotes:
    - The 'heaven-king's land' refers to the vast empire under imperial rule, likely during the Mongol Yuan dynasty period.
    - The 'axe of command' (鉞) symbolizes military authority and authority to act on behalf of the throne.
    - The 'purple palace' (紫宸) is a classical allusion to the imperial court.
    - Zhiyuan (至元) was an era name of the Yuan dynasty, suggesting an era of renewed peace and prosperity.
